ese remembrances-many of them appearing in English for the first time, each chosen for both literary and historical value-collectively spotlight the strange moral universe of the camps, as well as the relationships that prisoners had with one another, with their guards, and with professional criminals who lived beside them.A vital addition to the literature of this era,annotated for a generation that no longer remembers the Soviet Union, Gulag Voices will inform, interest, and inspire, offering a source for reflection on human nature itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConcentration campszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aForced laborzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aPolitical prisonerszSoviet UnionxSocial conditions. 0aPrisonerszSoviet UnionvBiography. 0aPrisonerszSoviet UnionxSocial conditions. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh1 aApplebaum, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Jane Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030015320040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016012340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300160123423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300160123/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY